<dl id="n12029b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12029b">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12029b"> 29(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> bards, vacerres, eubages / sacrifice augurs</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">II. Les Druides, connus aussi sous les noms de Bardes, Eubages, Vacies, Saronides, Samoth&eacute;es ou Simnoth&eacute;es, &eacute;toient distingu&eacute;s en trois principaux ordres. Les premiers &eacute;toient les Pr&ecirc;tres charg&eacute;s des sacrifices, des pri&egrave;res & d&apos;interpr&ecirc;ter<font color="green">[sic]</font> les dogmes de la Religion. (&hellip;) Les Bardes &eacute;toient commis pour chanter des vers (&hellip;) Les Eubages tiroient les augures des victimes. <br><font color="green">[II. The Druids, also known under the names of <mark>Bards, Eubages, Vacies</mark>, Saronides, Samothees or Simnothees, were distinguished by means of three major orders. The first were the Priests responsible for the <mark>sacrifices</mark>, the prayers and the interpretation of religious dogmas. (&hellip;) The Bards were charged with singing verses (&hellip;) The Eubages drew <mark>auguries</mark> from the victims.]</font> <small> M. Sabbathier, <a name="MSAD" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#MSAD"><cite title="source">Dictionnaire pour l'intelligence des auteurs classiques, Grecs et Latins</cite></a> (1773) 491</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
